#compdef buffdb
# =============================================================================
# buffdb — Marcus Eagan + Jacob Pratt's "Embedded storage
#          built for AI model management over gRPC.  Smart
#          machines don't need to read JSON, they only need
#          protocol buffers.  The world's first MODMS
#          (Machine-Oriented Database Management System),
#          built to support SQLite and eventually DuckDB as
#          backends." — a Rust embedded key-value + BLOB
#          store accessed exclusively via gRPC + Protocol
#          Buffers (no REST / JSON layer).  Designed for
#          machine-to-machine workflows where humans rarely
#          query the data directly.
#          Distinguishing from Redis, etcd, SQLite, and other
#          key-value / blob stores by:
#            - gRPC-NATIVE API — all client interactions go
#              through Protocol Buffers + gRPC; no HTTP/JSON
#              REST endpoints.  Distinct philosophy: "smart
#              machines don't need JSON."  Clients are
#              generated from .proto files.
#            - 2 DATA MODELS — separate stores for:
#                * KV (key-value)  — string→string mapping
#                                    optimized for small,
#                                    frequently-accessed
#                                    values (configs, secrets,
#                                    feature flags, AI model
#                                    hyperparameters)
#                * BLOB             — binary-large-object
#                                    storage for big payloads
#                                    (ML model weights, image
#                                    files, embeddings)
#                Both backed by SQLite (default) with metadata
#                tables tracking access patterns
#            - SQLITE BACKEND via rusqlite — embedded SQLite
#              engine compiled into the binary; no external
#              database server required
#            - DuckDB BACKEND (temporarily disabled) — analytic
#              workloads supported when stabilized
#            - 3 ROOT SUBCOMMANDS via clap derive:
#                * run (alias: serve)  — gRPC server with
#                                        configurable --kv-store
#                                        + --blob-store paths
#                                        + listen ADDR
#                                        (default [::1]:9313)
#                * kv (aliases: key-value, k-v) — direct KV ops
#                                                without
#                                                requiring the
#                                                gRPC server
#                                                running
#                * blob                — direct BLOB ops
#            - KV OPERATIONS:
#                * get (fetch) KEYS...     get value(s)
#                * set (put/save/store) KEY VALUE  set value
#                * delete (remove/rm) KEY  delete by key
#                * eq (equal/equals) KEYS...   check equality
#                * not-eq (unique/ne/neq) KEYS...  check inequality
#            - BLOB OPERATIONS:
#                * get (fetch) ID [MODE]   get BLOB by id
#                                          MODE: data | metadata | both
#                * store (put/save/set) FILE_PATH [METADATA]
#                                          store BLOB with optional metadata
#                                          ("-" reads stdin)
#                * update ID MODE          update BLOB
#                * delete (remove/rm) ID   delete BLOB
#                * eq-data IDS...          check data equality
#                * not-eq-data IDS...      check data inequality
#            - tonic gRPC FRAMEWORK — uses Sean McArthur's
#              tonic (the canonical Rust gRPC implementation)
#              for both server + generated client code
#            - tonic-build PROTO COMPILATION — generates Rust
#              code from .proto definitions at build time;
#              proto/ directory contains schema definitions
#            - PROCESS-EXIT STATUS for predicates — `eq` /
#              `eq-data` / `not-eq` / `not-eq-data` use exit
#              status to indicate result (0 = true, non-zero
#              = false) for shell-script integration
#            - STREAMING ASYNC via async-stream — bulk
#              operations return gRPC streams (e.g., listing
#              all keys yields a stream of KvEntry messages)
#            - FEATURE-GATED — `--features sqlite,binary,tracing`
#              etc. control which backends + CLI binary +
#              telemetry are compiled in
#          Used by: AI/ML production teams needing low-latency
#          configuration + model-weight storage with gRPC
#          schema enforcement, edge / IoT devices needing
#          embedded storage with M2M protocol, and as a
#          reference implementation of tonic + tonic-build +
#          rusqlite + clap derive + async-stream composition
#          in Rust gRPC services.
#
# Author:  Marcus Eagan (@marcuseagan) + Jacob Pratt
#          (@jhpratt on GitHub).  Released ~2023; current
#          version 0.5.0; active development through 2026.
#          License: Apache-2.0.
# Source:  https://github.com/buffdb/buffdb
#          https://github.com/buffdb/buffdb/blob/main/src/cli.rs
#          https://github.com/buffdb/buffdb/blob/main/Cargo.toml
#          https://buffdb.com (project site)
# CLI:     src/cli.rs — uses clap v4 derive (well-documented
#          elsewhere).  Headline library: **tonic** (the new
#          variant being documented here, opening Axis 24 —
#          gRPC).
# Library: tonic (https://github.com/hyperium/tonic —
#          "A native gRPC client & server implementation with
#           async/await support" — Sean McArthur + Hyperium
#           project team.  Distinct from all previously-
#           documented Rust libraries by being:
#              1. RUST-NATIVE gRPC IMPLEMENTATION — tonic is
#                 the canonical Rust gRPC framework, written
#                 directly against the gRPC-over-HTTP/2 spec
#                 (no FFI / no grpc-c bindings).  Distinct
#                 from grpcio-rs (Cgo bindings to gRPC C++)
#                 which preceded tonic but added C++
#                 dependency.
#              2. ASYNC/AWAIT FROM DAY ONE — tonic was the
#                 first major Rust gRPC framework built on
#                 async/await syntax (since Rust 1.39, 2019).
#                 Distinct from grpcio-rs (callback-based) +
#                 earlier Rust gRPC experiments.
#              3. tonic-build PROTO COMPILATION — generates
#                 Rust types + service traits + client structs
#                 from .proto files at Cargo build time:
#                   // build.rs
#                   fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
#                       tonic_build::compile_protos("proto/helloworld.proto")?;
#                       Ok(())
#                   }
#                 Generated code uses serde-like idioms;
#                 services implemented by impl-ing the
#                 generated trait:
#                   use helloworld::greeter_server::{Greeter, GreeterServer};
#                   #[derive(Default)]
#                   pub struct MyGreeter {}
#                   #[tonic::async_trait]
#                   impl Greeter for MyGreeter {
#                       async fn say_hello(&self, request: Request<HelloRequest>)
#                           -> Result<Response<HelloReply>, Status> {
#                           ... }
#                   }
#              4. HYPER HTTP/2 BACKEND — tonic uses Sean
#                 McArthur's hyper for HTTP/2 transport (gRPC
#                 mandates HTTP/2); same hyper used by reqwest
#                 (R649 Axis 16 opener).  hyper provides
#                 connection pooling, multiplexing, flow
#                 control.
#              5. tower MIDDLEWARE — tonic services compose
#                 with tower::Service trait for middleware
#                 (auth, retry, rate-limit, tracing, metrics).
#                 Same tower used by axum (Tokio's web
#                 framework).  Distinct from grpcio-rs (no
#                 middleware integration).
#              6. STREAMING — bidirectional streaming via
#                 futures Stream; client + server can both
#                 send + receive sequences of messages on a
#                 single RPC.  Same async stream model as
#                 tokio-tungstenite (R657 Axis 18).
#              7. TLS via rustls OR native-tls — opt-in TLS
#                 via Cargo features; mTLS supported (mutual
#                 client + server certificates).
#              8. INTERCEPTORS for cross-cutting concerns —
#                 tower::Service-based interceptors enable
#                 distributed tracing (OpenTelemetry), auth
#                 token validation, request/response logging
#                 across all RPCs.
#              9. tonic-reflection FOR REFLECTION — implements
#                 the gRPC Server Reflection protocol for
#                 dynamic service discovery (used by grpcurl,
#                 Postman, BloomRPC).
#             10. HYPERIUM PROJECT PROVENANCE — Sean McArthur
#                 + Hyperium team maintain:
#                   * hyper      — HTTP/1.1 + HTTP/2 backbone
#                   * reqwest    — high-level HTTP client      (R649)
#                   * tonic      — gRPC framework               (THIS)
#                   * tower      — middleware
#                   * warp       — web framework
#                 Sean McArthur becomes a 2-LIBRARY AUTHOR in
#                 the taxonomy (after reqwest R649).  Hyperium
#                 is the foundational Rust HTTP+gRPC stack.)
# License: MIT (tonic); Apache-2.0 (buffdb)
# Status:  tonic — 12,216+ stars on hyperium/tonic, ~100M
#          crates.io downloads (TOP-30 Rust crate by downloads);
#          foundational gRPC framework used by:
#            * Apache OpenDAL (gRPC service ports)
#            * Apache DataFusion Ballista (distributed query
#              execution)
#            * Apache Arrow Flight (high-speed data transport)
#            * Influx Data IOx (time-series database)
#            * Vector (Datadog observability pipeline)
#            * Linkerd2 (some control-plane components)
#            * Edgee (edge computing platform)
#            * SurrealDB (multi-model database)
#            * QuestDB Rust client
#            * Apollo Router (GraphQL gateway — some adapters)
#            * Lighthouse (Ethereum consensus client)
#            * NEAR Protocol (blockchain)
#            * 5000+ Rust applications
#          buffdb — 304+ stars on buffdb/buffdb; used by AI/ML
#          production teams + edge IoT.
#
